/*--------------------------------*- Choupo -*--------------------------------*\
  tartaricAcid_acidulation -- the SOLUTION-CHEMISTRY sub-study of the tartaric-
  acid plant (tutorials/plant/tartaricAcid).

  THE SIMULATION-STRATEGY POINT (see userGuide "Strategy for a partly-
  characterised process"): the plant flowsheet closes its MASS balance with
  MOLECULAR reactors (Engine B, choupoSolve).  But the acidulation liquor is a
  concentrated electrolyte brine, and whether gypsum (CaSO4) actually drops out
  -- and at what ionic strength / activity -- is a SOLUTION-CHEMISTRY question
  the molecular flowsheet cannot answer.  So we answer it HERE, in choupoProps
  (Engine A), with the rigorous ion model, and feed the conclusion back.

  HONEST MODEL BOUNDARY: the INORGANIC ions (Ca2+, SO4^2-, K+, Cl-) carry full
  Pitzer binary parameters (PHREEQC), so the brine activity and the gypsum Ksp
  are rigorous.  The ORGANIC tartrate ion has NO published Pitzer parameters --
  the run ANNOUNCES this and treats it on the Debye-Hueckel limiting term only.
  Pitzer-for-some, DH-for-the-rest, declared aloud.  Tartrate is a near-
  spectator for gypsum here anyway (the acidulated acid is mostly neutral
  H2Tart at this pH); the gypsum ceiling rests on the Ca-SO4 chemistry, which is
  fully parametrised.
\*---------------------------------------------------------------------------*/

application   choupoProps;
description   "Tartaric-acid acidulation liquor: rigorous Pitzer brine chemistry (Ca-SO4-K-Cl) + the gypsum precipitation ceiling, with tartrate honestly on the Debye-Hueckel limit (no published Pitzer params). Davies vs Pitzer shown side by side.";
verbosity     2;
